Arrays in JavaScript 🚀

An Array in JavaScript is a special type of variable used to store multiple values in a single variable.
Instead of creating many separate variables, arrays allow developers to organize and manage data efficiently.

Arrays are one of the most important concepts in JavaScript because they are used in almost every real-world application such as:

Student management systems
Shopping carts
Social media apps
Games
APIs and databases
Data analytics applications


let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];
Here:

fruits → Array name
"Apple" → First element
"Banana" → Second element
"Mango" → Third element


Characteristics of JavaScript Arrays ✨

1. Ordered Collection

Elements are stored in order.
let colors = ["Red", "Blue", "Green"];

2. Index-Based

Each element has an index number.
Element	Index
Red	0
Blue	1
Green	2

3. Dynamic Size

Arrays can grow or shrink automatically.
let numbers = [1, 2, 3];
numbers.push(4);
console.log(numbers);

Output
[1, 2, 3, 4]
4. Can Store Mixed Data Types
let data = [10, "Hello", true, null];
Creating Arrays in JavaScript 🛠️
Method 1: Using Square Brackets
let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

This is the most common method.

Method 2: Using Array Constructor
let fruits = new Array("Apple", "Banana", "Mango");
Accessing Array Elements 🔍

Use index numbers to access elements.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];

console.log(fruits[0]);
console.log(fruits[1]);

Output
Apple
Banana
Changing Array Elements ✏️


let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];
fruits[1] = "Orange";
console.log(fruits);
Output

["Apple", "Orange", "Mango"]
Array Length 📏

The length property returns total number of elements.

let numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40];

console.log(numbers.length);
Output
4
Important Array Methods 🔥
1. push() Method

Adds element at the end.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana"];

fruits.push("Mango");

console.log(fruits);
Output
["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"]
2. pop() Method

Removes last element.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];

fruits.pop();

console.log(fruits);
Output
["Apple", "Banana"]
3. shift() Method

Removes first element.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];

fruits.shift();

console.log(fruits);
Output
["Banana", "Mango"]
4. unshift() Method

Adds element at the beginning.

let fruits = ["Banana", "Mango"];

fruits.unshift("Apple");

console.log(fruits);
Output
["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"]
5. includes() Method

Checks if element exists.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];

console.log(fruits.includes("Banana"));
Output
true
6. indexOf() Method

Returns index position.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];

console.log(fruits.indexOf("Mango"));
Output
2
7. slice() Method

Extracts part of array.

let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

let result = numbers.slice(1, 4);

console.log(result);
Output
[2, 3, 4]
8. splice() Method

Adds/removes elements.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];

fruits.splice(1, 1);

console.log(fruits);
Output
["Apple", "Mango"]
9. concat() Method

Combines arrays.

let arr1 = [1, 2];
let arr2 = [3, 4];

let result = arr1.concat(arr2);

console.log(result);
Output
[1, 2, 3, 4]
10. join() Method

Converts array into string.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];

console.log(fruits.join("-"));
Output
Apple-Banana-Mango
Looping Through Arrays 🔁
Using for Loop
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];

for (let i = 0; i < fruits.length; i++) {
    console.log(fruits[i]);
}
Using for...of Loop
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];

for (let fruit of fruits) {
    console.log(fruit);
}
Using forEach()
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];

fruits.forEach(function(fruit) {
    console.log(fruit);
});
Advanced Array Methods ⚡
map()

Creates new array by transforming elements.

let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4];

let square = numbers.map(num => num * num);

console.log(square);
Output
[1, 4, 9, 16]
filter()

Filters elements based on condition.

let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];

let even = numbers.filter(num => num % 2 === 0);

console.log(even);
Output
[2, 4, 6]
reduce()

Reduces array to single value.

let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4];

let sum = numbers.reduce((total, num) => total + num, 0);

console.log(sum);
Output
10
find()

Returns first matching element.

let numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40];

let result = numbers.find(num => num > 20);

console.log(result);
Output
30
Multidimensional Arrays 📚

Arrays inside arrays are called multidimensional arrays.

let matrix = [
    [1, 2],
    [3, 4],
    [5, 6]
];

console.log(matrix[1][0]);
Output
3
